Duel on the knife edge: MP3 players against cell phones.
We will advise you on your choice
While almost any cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
So it looks like it's better to just buy a phone.
Nevertheless, there are plenty of reasons why you should get a player of your own.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It's hard to buy a really good expensive turntable to play the latest album of Maxim Turbulenc.
For one thing, such musical innovations do not appear on LPs, and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
But if you have art rock, jazz, or blues LPs on your shelves, you probably dream of at least one.
So it's the same with music on the road, with compressed music, in simple terms, MP3 music.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
It may not be acceptable for one person to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink Floyd fan will probably have difficulty withholding headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, with enough room for everyone in between.
The choice is wide.
The life of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players do more than play music, but what cell phones can do, they can't even hint at.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to its primary functions, calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, have a camera that's better and a camera that's worse, and maybe even navigate.
And if you add the smartphones and the communicators, you're almost a small computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no television can take pictures.
But the universality of mobile phones also has its drawbacks.
But the more features you use on your phone, the more you'll need to recharge it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy drainers.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, and most of them are much less.
Music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more powerful in this respect.
So, with cheap cell phones, you should expect that they won't play music for more than a few hours.
If you do use your phone occasionally, you may want to buy a charger for the office - even if it is more expensive.
You won't have this problem with MP3 players, even the less-than-good ones can last at least nine hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem is when you want to play the music on your cell phone.
Unfortunately, only a small number of devices have a USB port, and not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but few card readers can handle the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With Players, you don't need any special software, except for the iPod.
All you need to do is to feed the device music from your PC via USB port.
Most mobile phones and players create their own music library, sorted by artist name, album title, genre, or user rating, for example.
Some devices only map the tree structure of the address book, similar to Windows Explorer, some can both (river, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a particular device, you should ask about the battery life, the storage capacity, the quality and type of sound, and of course the ease of use.
If you listen to music in the background, for example, for a short time each day in the tramway, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files will suffice.
Which is what almost every cell phone can do.
You also do not have to control what music formats a mobile phone or a player can handle.
MP3's all created, and most of the music you're going to get is going to be in that format.
The format is one of the most common, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also allow people to buy music online.
All you have to do is go to the corresponding websites of a provider (or of another provider) via the mobile Internet, and you can already purchase a song or album.
This service may be a powerful argument in itself for why you should get a music phone.
Unfortunately, the service providers' offer is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest.
In general, however, it is expected that this particular form of music sales (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones with them.
If you want to listen to something, grab the phone in your jacket pocket while the player is at home.
However, it depends on whether you are always carrying headphones or at least a wireless speaker.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost every cell phone has, but very few MP3 players.
The biggest advantage of music phones will be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three or four thousand crowns you can get a decent Walkman.
The biggest handicap for most of them will be that they don't have normal headphones.
The best and most technically advanced phones with a 3.5 mm aperture for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the player is, in turn, the ease of use.
The simplest - and not necessarily the cheapest (see selection) - player can really be used by anyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the former normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no danger of a collision in the form of a misplaced mobile Internet and a subsequent horrendous bill for data transmissions.
What Tools Should You Use
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a card, two thousand crowns will be enough.
But beware.
The basic models generally only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can read 8GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and you want to buy a cheap MP3 player, go to Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you will then have to put no more than 1100 krona on the table.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, you should take specialized mobile phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent control buttons for MP3s, and the ease of operation is comparable to that of a single MP3 player.
The most advanced is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series of phones have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) are provided by MP3 players from the manufacturers mentioned above.
The first virtual provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe you do .
The Czech mobile market is quite mature, with Czech operators offering virtually all services as offered by their Western European counterparts.
However, there is something missing here - a virtual supplier that forces the classic ones to lower prices.
Perhaps this one will not be long in coming.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
The latest steps by the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges are likely to lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really does make a fight fan.
It may sound paradoxical, but there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and penetration is well over 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, are happy to complain that there is extreme competition on the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, often agrees with this.
It is likely that a traditional operator with its own network would not have much chance (and would also probably not be able to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual vendor.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market in particular led to a significant price reduction, to which the traditional operators also had to react.
The Commission has not yet decided whether to accept the amendments proposed by the rapporteur.
But it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February this year, we reported on the launch of the mobile virtual service provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the company has managed to attract more than 100 000 customers and become the fifth largest provider in the country.
The financial group behind Mobilking is Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that they can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, virtual providers need much fewer customers than a traditional provider.
The Commission has therefore decided to open the procedure provided for in Article 93 (2) of Regulation (EC) No 1191/1999.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, but often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, in the UK, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a very good move to target a non-stereotypical audience.
This is because this particular provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and trust", said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of the virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could also take root in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone's spokesman Miroslav Čepický also expressed doubts: 'The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services".
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators say they have no chance
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator takes over the Czech Republic, it will not be the mobile king.
"While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic are not looking particularly promising.
It will be more likely that Mobilking will enter the market in other countries in our region", said Jana Studničková, press spokesperson for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It confirmed indirectly that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
The interest of the GTS Novera Group in the launch of a virtual mobile operator has been evident for some time, as it wants to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer segment.
'We have a strong interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them", said Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesman.
Maybe there'll be better times to come.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far, it is surrounded by an impassable wall of silence.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech Republic for a full-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market has a high degree of specificity compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area", says Vlastimilše Srň from Telefónica O2's press department in his statement to Mobil.cz.
The specific character of the Czech market is also highlighted by other suppliers.
In a rare agreement with O2's statement, T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds: "So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build".
And she adds, "T-Mobile's network will barely have a virtual provider by the end of the year.
We would have to have a concrete offer at this moment to be able to think so short-term".
Vodafone is more concerned with meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický comments: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the best thing from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile Internet".
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the suppliers
The approach of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another operator would mean more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus to a decline in profits.
So why should one facilitate the entry of such a competitor?
The fact that suppliers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth around the emergence of U:fon.
The biggest pressure on ČTÚ was probably from T-Mobile, when U:fon was launched.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information on the ČTÚ website.
But U:fon is a good argument for not allowing a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: 'The competitive environment of the mobile communications market has also been recently strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, in particular, on its services.'
However, in view of this approach of the mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulators is surprising.
It is not just the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately - unlike the United Kingdom and other advanced countries - does not have the competence to interfere in economic competition.
The only owner of this office is the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical attitude to the whole problem.
'The entry of a virtual mobile operator into the market would be possible only after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional suppliers", said Kristián Chalupa, from the external relations department of the ÚOHS, in response to our inquiry.
The Commission has not yet been able to conclude that the aid is compatible with the common market.
This is more than a matter of concern for an authority which is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers operate normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price decrease in mobile telephone services".
However, it is unlikely that the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are in the interests of the ÚOHS.
The most striking thing about this case is the almost touching agreement between the three mobile operators, which is the result of their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
The same is true of the price of petrol at petrol stations, which is certainly the result of a hard competition.
'The Authority has not found any evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in this matter in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant position on the market and therefore has no corresponding increased responsibility for its actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market to virtual providers are also likely to be lacking in the telecommunications regulator", Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many controversial issues.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets, carried out by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators holds a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, take a different view - the entry of a virtual provider always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile phone operator has, logically, a monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a certain segment.
Even if one does not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the company GTS Novera mentioned above) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all the suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is a commonly used trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the extension of the competence of the ČTÚ to the area of economic competition in telecommunications was not implemented in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, although a number of experts had promised that this would improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
I'm fine if no one is looking
The functioning of some pseudovirtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, is not noticed.
They are companies which issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
These are usually companies that are involved in multilevel marketing.
The main sources of funding are the private sector, the public sector and the private sector.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only selected customers.
The irony is that the company is a classic corporate customer vis-à-vis the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a key customer, he receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit reselling of a similar nature.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will deal with, which may lead to the termination of cooperation with the relevant company", Martina Kemrová answered our question on this problem.
However, it is unlikely that this is not a matter of discussion among the operators of mobile telephony.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, it may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
The fact that the activities of these companies do not generate a negligible profit for them does not mean that they are not affected by the actual official marketing, unlike the actual virtual providers.
Miroslav Čepický points out the problems: "The law allows for these types of speculation, but the services of these companies are used by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have full control over it like normal customers of the mobile operators.'
But even that would make the CTU look strange.
In addition, there is another question for the ÚOHS.
The mobile operators are turning a blind eye to this, so why are they turning a blind eye to a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has a very strong competence to detect such activities and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers that they did not know about it and that their business conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As already emphasized in the text several times, the entry of virtual providers into the market has led to a significant fall in the price of the various services.
In practice, however, in all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence to a greater or lesser extent.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small or too saturated a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, it was precisely at this point that regulatory bodies intervened, not in the interests of the mobile operators but in the interests of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the first virtual operator, and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole thing at them like a hot potato.
In our experience, we cannot help feeling that in these cases the lack of clarity of the skills is more than beneficial.
But let's not throw the gun into the fire.
If the background information is correct and a virtual operator appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon be back on the move.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will no longer have to pay more for their telephones than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
