The Prague transport companies will also be using a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will go down in the history of Prague's public transport as the date on which the first passengers boarded a metro, tram or bus carrying an electronic ticket in their pocket instead of a paper one.
The Commission has already published a report on the implementation of the directive on the protection of consumers.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual voucher (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it added to their chip card at the same time, at the information centres and transport companies' branches at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Kobská Raj zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons are also available on the Internet at the transport companies' website www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon.
Those who use the Internet can really forget about the ticket window at the subway stations, where they regularly had to wait in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon online, and it is added to the open card in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, travellers can also use a desk with trained staff who can advise on buying online and also put the coupon on the card", says Martin Opatrný, the project's spokesman.
In addition to libraries, the electronic coupons can also be placed on the opencard at self-service vending machines installed in some subway lobbies.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket values, and passengers may have noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there will be eighty", Opatrný adds.
The coupon is checked by an automaton instead of the driver
The machines, which will be operational from tomorrow, are easy to operate.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the coupon you purchased will automatically be activated.
The electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
The suburban trains and buses with the numbers 300 to 499, which mainly carry residents of the municipalities of the Central Bohemian region, are used to reach the capital.
"In the trains that are part of Prague's integrated transport, the train attendants have readers that allow them to check the validity of the coupons by time and zone", explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid ticket control organisation, which compiles timetables for Prague's transport operators.
Suburban buses have map-reading devices at the cashier's desk.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but must be placed in a designated place at the side of the cash register.
This is used to check the validity of the coupons that have been used.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons that have been used, the easiest way is to ask the driver for this information", Drápal says.
A passenger who does not travel by suburban bus and does not know when the validity of the coupon will end can go to the vending machines where the coupons will be inserted on the card.
Here the information on the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States
The Sudeten Germans had asked for the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States in 1945.
