Rats have feelings too
A rat or a cockroach flees when in danger. Does that mean they feel fear too?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals have feelings too.
But how could you tell if they feel the same way if they're behaving the same way as us?
The online journal Edge has been publishing contributions from famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question "What do you believe to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else having been able to prove this before, since we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But as soon as we turn to other species and address questions of sense or consciousness in general, we're entering a very difficult terrain because the hardware is not compatible.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing that many other animals do - it kills itself, runs away, or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, leading some scientists to suggest a similar subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and executive/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the other primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there's reason to believe that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: Since so much of his experience is tied to language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness was independent of language, it would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, whatever its makeup, would likely be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
So it's hard to say what consciousness might look like in other animals.
If it is something internal and subjective, which cannot be measured or, because of the special hardware, analysed by our own experience, then its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of what I've said is about the content of conscious experience, but there's another aspect of consciousness that might be easier to access scientifically.
You could study the conscious processes of animals without regard to their content, and that's exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But this approach, which was pursued by Christoph Koch and Francis Crick, is more about the neural correlates of consciousness than the causal mechanisms, whether they are identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the development of visualization.
What does that say about the sensations?
I trace it back to the fact that an emotional system like fear is activated in a conscious brain of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is the mental state we are in when the activity of the defence system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies working memory.
So, in this sense, sensations are closely tied to the regions of the cortex that are characteristic of primates, and especially humans.
Connected with the nature of language, there are subtle gradations of feeling, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states, to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the body-sensory regions of the cortex and the brain stem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, but more focused on the brain stem.
Since this network hasn't changed much in the course of human evolution, it could well be involved in cross-genre feelings.
I cannot disagree with this in theory, but I think it is unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to feel like fear in both cases: But how can we test whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees when in danger, but does it also feel fear?
In my eyes, mere similarity of behavior is not proof of similarity of experience.
And the neural comparison helps us a lot, because rats and humans have similar brainstems, but mice don't even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it in humans, how would you prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours -- human consciousness is based on special circuits and language -- I prefer to study emotional behavior rather than emotional sensations in rats.
But at least here, progress is showing up at the neural level, if you measure the same in rats and humans.
I don't study language or consciousness in rats, and I don't study feelings, so I don't know if they exist.
This may seem short-sighted, but I'd rather move forward than keep running into walls.
I'm a practical emotionalist, you know.
