The debate on bilingual education: education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of the candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior fellow in California Studies and senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a coauthor of Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice.
Addressing the Hispanic electorate is a complicated task.
The proposals of Barack Obama on education are a typical example.
Obama's campaign notes that "African-American and Hispanic students are less likely to graduate than white students" - which is true.
To close this achievement gap, Obama's education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition in education for those who are learning English for the first time.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes teaching in languages other than English, is inconsistent with his interest in reducing the achievement gap.
Take Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in East Los Angeles, for example.
Most of the students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than one third of the students, many of whom have recently arrived in the country, are learning English.
Yet, in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth-graders passed the state examination in math at a good level.
Also surprising, 93 percent of the fourth-grade children scored well on the English test.
This amazing success has been achieved by methods other than those favored by Obama.
Sixth Street School emphasizes review and practice, constant scrutiny of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
The school also has an approach of teaching in an English-speaking environment, which is precisely the point Obama should be aware of, according to school director Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasises the almost exclusive use of English in the teaching of specialised subjects.
Mrs Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico, and that 12 months later, you would walk into the classroom and not be able to recognize him.
"It works", she remarked, "it works for us".
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with large percentages of Hispanic and other English-language learners?
The school's achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational positions within his own party (the national education associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama's answer uncertain.
While agreeing with the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about legislation aimed at "English only".
Instead, he said, "You're supposed to make sure your kid can speak Spanish".
If Obama really wants to close the achievement gap, he should carefully consider models of education that work, rather than belittle and trivialize them.
