Since last Monday, the price has dropped by over $20
In the past two weeks, commodity markets have been rocked by both the financial turmoil on Wall Street and by powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After peaking at $145.29 a barrel in July, prices fell to almost $90 a barrel this month, only to rise again as a result of the enormous uncertainty in the financial markets.
On Monday, investors were once again worried, despite congressional officials announcing that they had agreed to a bailout over the weekend, which was to be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis was far from over.
In the latest chapter of the growing crisis, a government announcement Monday that Citigroup will buy the banking business of Wachovia Corporation.
In the meantime, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalised the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a rescue plan, it seems to have failed to revive the mood in the markets.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, demand for goods, including oil, is expected to continue to decline.
In a note to investors, Deutsche Bank analysts said that forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates had become extremely uncertain.
We believe, they write, that the commodity markets will also be affected.
"From a commodity market perspective, our biggest concern is whether the US virus is spreading globally, especially to China".
The Bank's analysts have revised downwards their expectations for oil consumption for the coming year, due to weak economic growth, and have cut their forecasts for oil and gas prices for 2009 by 20%.
Team record by series in the second quarter
Center Shaun Ellis thought he'd seen it all, after being caught in the Jets uniform more than anyone else in the last eight and a half years.
Then he saw the second quarter on Sunday, when the Jets turned a scoreless game into a triumphal parade.
"I've never seen anything like it", said Ellis.
After a sloppy game between the Jets and the Arizona Cardinals, which was due to bad weather, the second quarter began.
But when quarterback Brett Favre's pass to Lavernues Coles for a 12-yard touchdown marked the perfect start to an afternoon where their evolving partnership took a giant leap forward.
Favre found Coles in that quarter for two more touchdowns, one as a quarterback slipping and the other 10 seconds before halftime.
"I didn't try very hard", Coles said of the passes that went to Coles.
"He's a great player.
Our vote was right, no matter what people think".
As Favre and Coles played catch, defensive quarterback Kurt Warner took over.
Outfielder Darrelle Revis intercepted a fumble and converted it into a 32-yard touchdown.
Libero Erik Smith came to another pass and intercepted him.
Linebacker David Bowens then provided a loss to Warner.
That last ball loss, forced on Bowens, was probably the craziest.
The Cardinals had the ball with 10 seconds left in the game when the Jets recovered the ball and Jay Feely converted a 20-yard shot to take a 34-to-nothing lead.
That's the most points the Jets have ever scored in a quarter.
Asked to describe the insanity, Jets coach Erik Mangini replied, "The second quarter or the third quarter?"
When asked if he liked both, because the Jets allowed 21 unanswered points in the third quarter, Mangini said, "Believe me, I enjoyed the second quarter more than the third.
A lot of points were scored in a short time".
A rested baby-beater beats his world record
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia has shown once again why some consider him the greatest long-distance runner of all time, after breaking his own record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to complete the 42.2-kilometer distance in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the victory on the flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous result of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has set his 26th world record in a varied career in which he has won at least one world title or set a world record on every distance from the mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon, fearing that the air pollution might worsen his asthma problems, which was perhaps exaggerated in retrospect.
Instead, he's signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions - with sunshine and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie won with an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since track runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya switched to long distance, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the last 10 years, since Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 1998 with 2:06:05.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had had cramps in his calf two weeks ago and therefore could not train for a week.
Apparently, he came back refreshed after a break, not rusty.
"I'm so happy", he told reporters.
"Everything went perfectly.
I started training again a week ago and I had some concerns today, but in the end everything was great".
He has been criticized - especially in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rivals - for orchestrating his races excessively, generally avoiding many of the world's top marathon stars, relying too heavily on the race leaders as if it were a track race, and setting world records over the competition.
But this criticism does little to diminish Gebrselassies' stature as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the midpoint of the distance in 1:02:04.
Two elite runners from Kenya, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, continued to challenge Gebrselassie after the pace makers had slowed down.
With just over three miles to go, Gebrselassie made his final attempt to break away from Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his best by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, originally from Kazakhstan and now a German, completed a remarkable year by setting the seventh fastest time of all time with 2:19:19.
The world record of 2:15:25 is held by Paul Radcliff of Great Britain.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko had surprisingly won the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games due to problems that were described as a back injury, but recovered to win in Berlin and improve her best time in her third marathon by five minutes.
She planned her run well, putting a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners in the race, but overtaking them after 30 kilometers.
Askale Tafa Magarsa from Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop from Kenya came in third in 2:25:01.
The pride and the struggle of the black population in a city of a very special kind.
Hidden among the excesses of the Orlando area's amusement parks, a few miles from the glittering, noisy, gigantic bustle, lies a quiet town where the pride and complications of African-American culture are on display.
Eatonville, the first all-black town in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the town with 5 lakes, 3 croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough caves, 2 schools and no jail".
Nowadays it's a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the town she describes - which she made a tourist destination by including it in the Florida Travel Guide produced by the Federal Writer's Project during the Depression - is and remains in many ways a very special place.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man, who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing".
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about race relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told", said Hortense Jones, 59, a native of the city and a parishioner of the city's oldest church.
It must be true".
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historic example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 people with a poverty rate twice the national average.
It is a bastion of literature on the one hand, and an example of the sometimes condemned, sometimes praised, black culture of the rural South, rooted in American slavery, on the other.
It's not surprising that the people here are both proud and wary.
And so the concern about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown in books that came from the heart and were written in the mouth, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida travel guide changed the city, which is located very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the theaters of black history and human drama.
Freaky as Oscar in real life and literature, Hurston led Leser to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private matters.
"Across the street to the left", she wrote, "is the brown-and-white-painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always takes care of, even though he can barely read and write".
She also mentioned the new husband of Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever-ever fits the hours".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriages and sex.
This was definitely not a guidebook.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were", said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston, quoting the men singing songs about their beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added: "Some people did not like this".
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came into town in a hurry, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today imagines something of its venerable dress style.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the townspeople were fascinated, but many were disgusted.
"People were always glad to see Zora", said Mr. Franklin.
"But she never stayed too long", he added as he rocked in his chair on a back-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, in which Hurston was likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary of Langstin Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
There were no big commemorations in Eatonville, no public readings in a big way.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy in the slightest", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a 2003 biography of Hurston.
The turning point came in the '80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to lay a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane highway.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult phase in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950's, the struggle against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"In those days a lot of white boys would come in and throw oranges and stuff at the people sitting on the sidelines", said Mr. Franklin.
"There was even a woman killed in the process.
They threw a watermelon out of the car".
In 1955, Hurston wrote to the Orlando Sentinel questioning the Supreme Court's call to enforce integration, calling its decision in Brown v. School Board "insulting rather than respectful of my race".
Residents now say that while the removal of segregation was positive in some ways, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning and you hugged your teacher in the evening", says N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there is a cultural divide", Ms. Nathiri said.
But civil rights helped make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons -- black writers, actors and artists who overcame prejudice as she did, with positive self-esteem and statements like, "How can anyone deny themselves the joy of my company!
I don't understand it at all".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out to find Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight to restore her fame.
Five years later, a much-lauded biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves, making her part of the American literary canon once again.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The town began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could do with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway brought the city to life, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, and created a real sense of civic pride", said Ms Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd put it a little more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory against the long-distance road project has contributed to a change in the city's image.
More and more train wreckers came, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who's been attending church here since 1993, and locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new single-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a distinctive part of Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(She's 90% black these days.)
Outsiders seeking to learn about the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
Most interviews require prior approval, and certain things - such as the mural at Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man depicting black men working in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a penchant for dark-skinned, still fear that her secluded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival was growing, so was an increased sense of pride in one's hometown.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw his entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, no better or worse, and just as proud, creative and industrious, silly and mixed as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that you can hear in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in city government or the police, who he says could use some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville right.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, 'Oh, this town is nothing compared to all the others,'" said Alondra Kenon the other day after church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city".
Here in New York, we speak fluent Latin for finance.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan were to turn away from the newsstands and the giant TV screens in Times Square, they would not even realize that they were in the midst of a debacle.
You would never believe that, above their heads, in their shoe-box-like offices with the glass facades, the bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York have the worst horror workday since the 1929 stock market crash.
The suppliers are still loudly clapping as they push the metal tea carts along sidewalks and carry muffin-laden tablets for the breakfast seating.
Latinos still shuffle between apartments like human pack animals loaded with 50 ironed T-shirts suspended from a yoke-like rod on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting for their breakfast bagels at the sidewalk food stalls, and it is still impossible to get a yellow cab on a weekday between 4 and 7 p.m.
It didn't feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon, when all this doomsday talk made me decide to open a new savings account.
Although I had decided to leave my duty in the quiet late afternoon at my JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about 20 people in line.
Not at the cash desk to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk where regular customers order cheque books, tourists ask for directions to Macy's, and where new customers open accounts.
Most of the people in front of me, I later learned from Starr, my "personal licensed bank clerk", were standing in line for the same reason I was standing in line.
But unlike me, they had already taken their savings from smaller banks in places they commuted from, like New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They had taken money from what they called thrifts, cooperative banks and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state, and they say they treat their customers like family.
In the last year, 15 of these banks have gone quietly bankrupt.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went into receivership, and as New Yorkers drove home for the weekend last Friday, Wachovia, another bank with $440 billion in savings, was looking for a rescue buyer.
Fearful of another collapse, the office and store employees in the queue before me took their cash to a bank considered a safe haven, a bank responsible for most of the bailout purchases on Wall Street.
Normal New Yorkers have been embracing fluent financial Latin in recent weeks.
A woman who called at my Chinese supermarket made a familiar reference to Lehman Brothers, the failed bank and its emaciated-looking CEO Dick Fuld, as if she were slandering a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-something uniformed concierge of my apartment block, has moved away from our usual conversations about Brad and Angelina and my grocery delivery.
"I have now put all my savings into money market funds", she told me after my visit to the bank.
"I've changed my mind, I'm not taking any more risks".
Muslim graves desecrated during a legal landslide in Austria
Heinz-Christian Strache, a left-wing member of the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party of Austria, and Filip Dewinter, a member of the Belgian right-wing party Pertei Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, 17 January 2008, to represent the organisation Cities against Islamisation.
They carry signs in the style of traffic signs, with a mosque, crossed with a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a grave at a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same weekend that far-right parties are making significant gains in the country's parliamentary elections.
In the night from Friday to this morning, more than 90 graves were damaged in the cemetery in Traun near Linz in what police say was an organized action.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols such as the David Stern on some of the graves, but law enforcement officials believe this was an attempt to obscure the motive of extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is in any way connected to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Muslim community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the grave desecration, which took place as the religious month of Muslim Ramadan draws to a close.
At the same time, Austria is facing a round of soul-searching after the country's rightward slide in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The FPÖ and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties that won almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for a strict anti-immigrant law and some of their slogans were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, leader of the FPÖ, which won 18% of the vote, called for a ban on headscarves and burqas and even expressed his aversion to foods commonly associated with Islam.
In his last speech in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets with the argument that these are political symbols of a continuing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses carried out immediately after the election, which indicate that the far right is the strongest political bloc in the country, suggest that this new development is based on young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
External travel ban for Gary Glitter
Gary Glitter, the glam rock star convicted of child sexual abuse, has been barred from traveling to France and Spain.
Judges imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the authorities controlling him that he wanted to travel via France to Spain.
Kent police were granted a travel ban last Thursday after they presented evidence to judges of Glitter's prior convictions for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford District Court in Kent, but was represented by the law firm Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the Court reported: 'On Thursday, 25 September, the Kent Police requested permission from the Ashford District Court to prevent Mr Paul Glad from travelling abroad to France and Spain until 25 March.
Paul Gadd was not in person".
As required by the sex offender registry, Glitter, 64, had informed the authorities that he intended to travel abroad.
He has to notify the authorities if he wants to go abroad for more than three days.
He must also notify the police seven days before he plans to leave.
Failure to notify the authorities could result in a prison sentence of up to five years.
Kent police said they would not discuss individual cases or Glitter's possible whereabouts in the country.
A spokeswoman for the Kent Police Service said: "The Kent police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country and abroad".
"We believe it is easier to monitor someone in the UK because we have a comprehensive system to effectively prevent any potential risks".
"The Kent Police's primary concern is to protect the people of Kent and we work closely together to monitor the behaviour of registered sex offenders in the county to minimise any risk to the public.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, Glitter flew to Bangkok, where he was scheduled to take a flight to London.
But he said he wasn't feeling well and refused to fly to London.
The Thai authorities refused to let him pass through passport control and he flew back and forth to Hong Kong.
The Chinese authorities also refused him entry and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and border officials insisted that he return to the UK.
He finally arrived at Heathrow's Terminal 3 on 22 August and remained there while his lawyer, David Corker, went to the Uxbridge District Court in West London, after Scotland Yard successfully applied for permission to require him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter had previously been jailed for 4 months in the United Kingdom in 1999 for possession of child abuse images.
According to the Home Office, Home Secretary Jacqui Smith is reassured and satisfied that Glitter has been prevented from travelling to France and Spain.
