Drivers who may fall back because of the alcohol level will have to install the 'Alcollock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who has had three official penalties for the alcohol level, install in his car this system, which prohibits him from starting the car while drunk. If he is drunk, the car does not jump.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the Attorney General's report, which they say is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is to re-socialize the driver, which is why he receives a course for re-educating traffic behaviour.
In addition to the Attorney General's Office, it is also known that the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for Automobile Safety will be involved.
Statistics show that between 30 and 75% of drivers who have been cited more than once for driving under the influence of alcohol have returned to the wheel.
The `alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver has had an alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration is found that is higher than that allowed.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, and the costs are borne by the person who imposes the sanction.
In this context, a study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of the infringements in the first year of its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a crime.
And to facilitate their implementation, statutory reform can be achieved through the usual means, and yet requires a reform of the Basic Law, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market, in any store, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
The House of Representatives will be voting tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses.
