Talking in your sleep
Some children talk at night
I am not talking about the children who wake up and tell us what happened the day before, but the children who talk in their sleep.
When it happens to you for the first time, you'll be shocked at best, but in reality it doesn't matter.
This is a positive sleep disorder called sleep talking.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
Surely more than one of you has been told that you spoke at night.
This phenomenon may occur occasionally (once in a lifetime, for example, during a high fever) or regularly (every day, once a week, once a month), and the child may not remember anything the next day.
There is no single cause that causes this phenomenon.
Often, associations are sought with other phenomena in sleep, such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis, sleep talking, but there is no reason for this.
As we mentioned earlier, it can be due to very high fiber, stressful situations or overstrain.
Anyway, this is a little-studied phenomenon.
The frequency with which it occurs is very variable.
It may be that you speak quietly in individual words, whisper or it may be quite the opposite (screaming, crying, long discussions).
In cases where the expression is very intense, it is recommended that the child be observed and consulted by a specialist to check whether there is a problem that is causing anxiety and is thus brought about.
We've said that it's a positive disorder, so it's not being treated, whether it's related to another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, sleep apnea or stress).
What you can do is to take a series of simple precautions:
Try not to excite the child before he goes to sleep.
So choose quiet play for the child and avoid stressful TV programs that are horrible and a little too wild.
For nervous children who are recommended to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them to gain a measure of inner calm.
This helps the child to sleep peacefully.
If sleep talking occurs, try to keep calm.
Remember, it's harmless to the child and the next day he won't remember anything that happened.
Helpful Advice for the Young
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because the child is unconscious, so you'll tear it out of sleep.
Although the child is talking, he is sleeping, so he is resting.
Remember, if it shows fear after a few appearances, it is recommended to seek counseling or to find out what the reason is for the child's fear.
If they understand what is said (which is not so common), the child will not be pressured to conduct an interrogation and to get more information.
You will not be able to achieve anything by doing so, because when the child sleeps, it is unconscious and cannot think about it.
Also, you'll hear what he's saying, but you won't know what he's dreaming and why he's saying it, so be careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Maybe don't tell the kid that you hear it at night and know its secrets.
Not even as a joke.
