Discourse - Of the blood that was safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be pleased that Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And most importantly, it has restored the public's trust, which had been shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood banks administered by the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with the HIV virus and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In view of this tragedy and the public outcry, in February 1994 the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry, headed by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to develop policies to prevent a recurrence of such a disaster.
While Justice Krever was still reluctant to hand in his report, several provinces formed a committee to develop a new system for managing blood banks in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this commission.
According to Gélineau and Krever's reports, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
∀In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started its work, just 38% of people had confidence in the Quebec blood conservation system, Dr Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood products and the work in this area over the following years, we have regained the public's trust,' she says, before proudly noting that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary is aware that 'trust is extremely fragile'.
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been operating on the principle of prudence.
At that time, we saw the emergence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine mania in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since the foundation in 1998.
And we had no idea whether this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We have therefore referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which states that exclusionary measures are taken if this is not known and if a disease is slow to progress, as is apparently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself in a degeneration of the brain which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proved beyond all doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
So this incident has shown us that the precautionary principle we have applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate HIV detection technique appeared on the market: the nucleic acid test (NST), which makes it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the donor's blood, and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used previously.
The NSTs have made it possible to shorten the incubation period, which takes place between the time the person is infected and the first viruses detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
This has greatly reduced the risk that certain donors may be infected without knowing it and not being able to detect it.
These improvements have made it possible to reduce considerably the risk of transmitting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving blood contaminated with HIV.
In other words, you would have to give out 12 million units of blood before you could infect someone with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV was transmitted through a blood can.
I think that nowadays, it is possible to feel comfortable with receiving or prescribing blood transfusions to restore health,' says the director of Hema-Quebec.
∀Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen might be able to get into the system.
Only last year, the Chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects through blood, appeared on the island of Réunion.
We must be constantly monitoring,' Dr. Décary continues, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide a safe supply of healthcare, but also a sufficient supply.
∀Demand is increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer-fighting treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donation network, which on average includes only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate blood.
It is open to any healthy person 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria to donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of donors are rejected because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is common are barred from donating blood for one year.
∀With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get old and can't donate blood anymore.
It's hard to get people to give blood, but it's hard to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic today that it is rare to find the time to spend an hour donating blood,' laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, used almost exclusively for serious burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being interim stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, once considered a biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago we celebrated the stocking of our thousandth cord blood sample, and we plan to take more than a thousand a year.
'We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,' continues Dr Décary, who describes this programme of cord blood draw ing as very popular.
ˇ Many mothers feel they have no access to it because Hema-Quebec lacks the resources to offer this complex and costly programme in all Quebec hospitals.
