Free thought - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In its issue of 17 September, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director-General of the Canadian gold mine Barrick Gold.
The report confirms, in an Orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company was seeking to bring a libel action against three authors and a small publishing house with no money, seeking to open a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, then they are not judging the truth, especially not in the case of libel cases, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to bankrupt anyone who dares to hold an opinion that goes against theirs.
No matter how the trial goes, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and to fight with very unequal arms against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold miners.
The tactic in these unequal battles is often to ruin the defenders in order to force a compromise that will silence the other side and also discourage anyone from taking up the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her views to the public.
Unlike what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, debates are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas rather than by baton-whipping.
So it would have been enough if the gold mines had released their books and files and opened up a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent review teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and is sweeping aside the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a wave of the hand.
Could Mr Garver explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate and yet disregard the opinions of that very public?
It seems that in the vice-president's world, that word only covers the lavishly paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a pretty narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada do so primarily because they oppose the brutal attitude of the gold miners.
This public is willing to listen and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilised exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag lawsuit (during the 'public debate' Barrick Gold has just issued a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, asking them to stop using this term...).
Apart from the surreal speech of Mr. Garver, the Barrick Gold lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic inquiry and the search for truth that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to explore and debate issues that are not to the liking of the rich corporations of the world, who else can do it?
