What was produced in the invoicing factory of Zuschlag & Co.?
On October 8th, the trial of János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The defendants are accused in particular of involvement in organised crime, as well as gross negligence, damage and fraud, and other criminal acts, including forgery of documents.
According to the prosecutor's office, the proceeds from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often documented with fake invoices.
The State funds and grants from the local government - a total of HUF 65 million - are said to have been channelled partly into the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organisation and partly into the private coffers of individuals.
The investigation authorities announced that fictitious invoices had been presented when the tendering money was withdrawn and that the associations had not fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were faked.
The blocks were bought at the market of Józsefváros, the circular seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue the invoices was made on the round trip north of Lake Plateau, to which István Lados was sent by János Zázár.
During this "exploration tour", Lados was to search for guesthouses and restaurants.
He requested invoices on consumption, so that later on he could issue invoices for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, and the Budapest Municipality on the basis of these forms.
The majority of these calculations were allegedly manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who, according to our information, was responsible for the preparation of the corresponding reports.
One of the targets of Lados' "exploration tour" was a beer hall.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and Co in 2003, the catering establishment hosted the 90-strong group of the Biztos Pont Egyesület association.
Now, however, the head of the factory says that such a large group would not have been able to fit into the restaurant at one time.
Another invoice, issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also showed serious errors of form and content.
A pension in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at a time, is said to have been used by 130 guests.
The imagination of the accounting forgers was also apparently unlimited when it came to Pigal Kft., a catering company, in whose accounting records the documents of the customers Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá did not even appear, according to the prosecution.
As the managing director Győző Farkas told hvg.hu, he immediately knew that the documents were forged when he was presented with them by the prosecutor's office during an interrogation.
"Our company name and tax number were wrongly stamped on the stamp".
Furthermore, apart from the formal errors, the fact that the establishment was supposed to have accommodated 100 persons was also incorrect, since it has a total of 11 rooms which cannot possibly accommodate that many persons.
The bill also listed food and drink, but the restaurant had been out of business for a while.
The eager counterfeiters also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they targeted only offered travel abroad, and so they indicated Hungary travel on the cash invoice, which also contradicted the company's invoicing practices.
The investigation revealed that they also invoiced VAT, although travel agency services relating to a country outside the EU are exempt from VAT.
The amount of VAT was incorrect on four invoices issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the company only charged 15%, instead of 25%, and the employees issued invoices only by machine, but the falsified documents were handwritten.
Another error made by the accountants was that they had indicated in a case of "transport of goods" as a service provided, although this is not offered by the company specializing in investment advice, the prosecutor said.
Further formal errors - incorrect invoice format, incorrect stamp - were the reason why the invoices issued to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, as well as to XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont could be exposed as forgeries.
The same was true of Ravenna Bt. and Kunfehértó Sport Camp, whose managers claimed that they had never issued the invoices.
Another 'mistake' was made by the forgers at HIB Kft. from Nyíregyháza: this company was in the process of being dissolved at the time (2001) when the group of the Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have dined there - the mass manager therefore stated that he had not issued the invoices himself.
Forged deliberately
The other group of accountants are people who were quite aware that they would have to put fictitious invoices.
The Foundation has issued invoices to the Foundation Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, for an amount of approximately HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the managing director of Collab Ltd. was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue the fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft., which is also currently in liquidation, is also alleged to have cooperated with Zuschlag and Co. In 2003, the GmbH is alleged to have supplied the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, and the Atlasz Egyesület and Vörösfenyő Egyesület with fake invoices for a total value of HUF 5 million, relating to unpaid services.
However, there was also little payment as the invoices were cancelled immediately after they were issued, something which the persons concerned failed to mention in their documents.
The third group of accountants includes persons directly associated with the defendants.
One of them is Ivan Kubatov, the messenger of the Ukrainian manager of Delta Trió Kft., a fuel and vehicle trading company based in Budapest but not to be found there.
This company is said to have issued several invoices for the sale of computer components in the period from October to December 2005 for a total value of approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigating authority, Cash Investment Kft. from Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, acted as the buyer of these invoices.
The managing director of this company was a Romanian, to whom the company documents were also to be delivered by Iván Kubatov, between 2002 and 2005.
According to our information, during the investigation, Kubatov admitted to having issued invoices in the name of the company to the associations Atlasz and Hoppá, as well as to the Harmadik Évezred Alaértpítvány and to having collected the equivalent of them himself.
The companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos Investment Bt. were allegedly founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Iván Kubatov.
In reality, none of these companies were active, which the defendant said was due to a lack of orders.
Nevertheless, he was able to benefit from the companies: at the request of his accomplice, the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who was in charge of preparing the company's founding documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations associated with the procurement, such as Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
In total, Kubatov is alleged to have issued 15 invoices to the organisations, with a total value of HUF 14,2 million, on behalf of the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade.
The prosecution believes that Kubatov may have collected 10% of the invoice and 10% of the VAT.
Kubatov even allegedly abused the company Szi-Beri Bt. for the issuance of fictitious invoices - in this case, the invoices were attached to the applications of Biztos Pont.
The Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért companies submitted their applications to the non-profit organization of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány ("TMA") in January 2006.
Both received 500 000 forints each, but misappropriated these amounts.
In order to cover up this, they submitted to the TMA five fictitious invoices of Works Team Kft.
These accounts were, incidentally, secured during the search of Árpád Kemecsei's office in the Ministry of Education.
The negotiations now include a number of defendants who are expected to confess to the fraudulent accounting procedures as they have already been presented to the public prosecutor.
It could be a sensation if the main defendant, János Zuschlag, decides to make a full confession.
His previous statements were less detailed, and although he has already promised on several occasions to report fully on everything, his confession is still pending.
The question therefore remains whether this is in his interest, whether the Socialists have made a pact with him to compensate the bulk of the HUF 50 million in damage incurred, and whether Zuschlag is prepared to accept responsibility in return.
It is possible that Zuschlag is now playing the "defendant" after his pleas for relief of imprisonment and house arrest were ignored.
While other criminals who have caused far greater damage through economic crime and have not repaid it are at large, or at least under house arrest, Zuschlag is denied this opportunity.
The Psychology of Over-selling - or Why We Are Willing to Pay More
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in uncovering the neuroeconomic basis of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in Science magazine, people are willing to pay exorbitant prices to avoid being beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay.
Researchers have tried to explore the neurological pattern of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was asked to play the lottery while the other participated in a game - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants won money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the overbid of the opponent plays a significant role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-rewarding" function of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally conducted studies on the tracking of money.
In this case, three groups should bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was told the true value of the product, and then they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward if they emerged victorious from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a losing game.
The difference between the two groups was that the emphasis was on winning, while the other group was on losing.
But as evidence of the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to bet more than those in the control or "winning" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
The behaviour observed in auctions has so far been justified by the pleasure of winning or the avoidance of risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved by the use of imaging neuroscience, and we now have a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When to See a Doctor
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is listed as the leading cause of death in Hungary.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are being treated, because patients often don't know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - hepatitis and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases are different.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two ways, depending on the pathogen: in hepatitis A and E, they can be transmitted through the digestive tract (e.g., through contaminated food or water); in hepatitis B, C, and D, viruses can be transmitted through blood and other bodily fluids (such as semen, vaginal secretions, or saliva).
Vaccination against A and B viruses is recommended for travellers, but there is no vaccine against C virus.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after the contaminated food is eaten and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and in the eyes, stool becomes light, urine dark, and recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B-related diseases, as well as more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people are on medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most people who are infected do not even know they have the disease because the pathogen is killing the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20 or 30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
Three groups are more likely to have the disease: those who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of people with chronic hepatitis C worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is detectable by routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult a family doctor at the first sign of an unknown origin.
If caught in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first observed by patient organisations worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the campaign is to raise awareness of this chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, its origin and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
Recent research has shown that religious faith acts as a kind of "pain-killer" that has been said to have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment to determine how belief in God affects a person's perception of pain, reports the British newspaper Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre experiment, 12 believers and 12 atheists were each given electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
The results showed that the faithful were able to eliminate much of the pain.
In fact, by means of brain-scan technology, it was demonstrated that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
The study was the first in a research project involving not only scientists but also philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
In the experiment, a flashing device was attached to the left hand of the subject, which gave the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus their attention on two paintings: one of the Virgin Mary, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and the other of Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermillion".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would induce a kind of religious trance among the faithful, while they chose da Vinci's picture because it was hardly different from the other painting and was considered soothing.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and during this time received a total of 20 electrical shocks in four stages, while they were asked to look at either the religious painting or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "cared for", and they felt "calm and peaceful".
When they looked at the religious painting, they reported over 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that similar effects could be produced by other powerful images in the atheists, just by finding the right one.
"We would have to find an image that would evoke very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father", said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the findings.
"The practice of faith should change our personalities, and in many cases does", Wright says.
After these excellent results, the question remains, what effect would a Madonna painting by Leonardo or another similar painter have on the pain regulation of the faithful?
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary produce even better results?
You Are What You Say You Are
On its tenth birthday, Google can rightfully claim that it's in people's pockets as much as it is above their heads in the sky: it knows where people have spent their holidays, which doctors they go to, and what motivates them.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the chief executives of Google.
To skeptics who are plagued by Orwellian horrors, he warns: they are missing the very essence of Web 2.0.
In a recent interview with the Financial Times, Schmidt said that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, moving closer to the company's original goal of "organizing all the information in the world".
Schmidt explained that after ten years of world-changing work, Google was still in the early stages of gathering information.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google could answer questions such as "What should I do tomorrow?" or "Which job is really for me?" but software programs are not yet able to do so because they do not know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that their Internet searches would record the search terms, the IP addresses used to search and the pages visited.
For example, the 'personalized search' introduced two years ago allows the visitor to save his own search history and access it later, so that hits can be generated much more accurately later, and the same logic underlies the so-called 'recommendations', which the system uses to recommend tailor-made products and services based on previous preferences.
However, users are wondering what happens in case of data abuse - "If you look at what I do" - some are worried about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is the potential power represented by the company that is feared, rather than the guilt or fear of punishment, the quest for freedom or the rebellion against power that is rejected by many Internet users.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored but also passed on to third parties when necessary, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A recent example of this was the recent action taken against pedophilia in Brazil, where Google gave the Brazilian government information collected from the community site called "Orkut" that also allowed for the identification of pedophilia.
However, users concerned about their privacy rights were still able to breathe a sigh of relief in May when Google, together with the civil rights organization EFF, successfully sued the FBI: according to this, Google can no longer be forced by any constitutional provision to provide information to the FBI on secret request.
(Although the German government has successfully obtained the release of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms, referring to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago, it has been deprived of the list of individual users, or their web and search terms list, retroactively for two months.)
Google's image remains controversial: Those who are reluctant to give their personal data out because they fear the loss of their privacy and privacy by using Google services are lashing out at the company with the indignation that is due to the companies that portray themselves as conservative.
However, the American "geek culture" that is present in many countries and brings together enthusiastic computer enthusiasts, activists and users, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, in contrast to Microsoft, which thanks to Windows is the market leader, even if both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require identification codes from its users and provides its services free of charge, so that an open source, constantly updated code and software package appear to be far more attractive, youthful and cool than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, geeks have a keen eye for the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet - a relationship that has come to the forefront in recent years, especially thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
The Web 2.0 is about collaboration, meaning that users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and although the dimensions vary individually, the main thing remains the same: to show up in public.
The average teenager can manage their profile on multiple community portals at the same time - from Facebook to Xanga, they can link it to other services like Twitter, or music services like last.fm, and they can eventually integrate all of this into a tracking system like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and they can also keep blogs that automatically show the latest photo galleries uploaded to Flickr or Picasa.
And a series of other examples prove that when looking at the party photos from the previous night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend had fun with, or the employee is fired for expressing his anger at the company's management in his blog with too much honesty - one thing is certain: the term "privacy" has been completely reinterpreted.
The online life is what you give away - that's the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who's trying to keep something secret, or even bypass Google's monopoly, can do that with ease -- like with Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google's search engine but deliberately leaves no trace.
Many people deliberately do not register on community sites so that they cannot be found, but also Google's online applications, such as word processing and graphic tools and RSS feeds, can handle alternative versions that are not tied to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile of the user.
Meanwhile, the public is waiting for Google to reveal its true face.
