A Smart Car That Imitates the Flight of a Bumblebee
What better way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents than to imitate the obstacle sensors in nature?
Take the bees, for example.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was unveiled, where the Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees in creating new crash-avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C car-robot-driven biomimetic system, a mini-car with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collision.
"In flight, each bee forms its own oval 'private space' that is very similar to our own 'protective shield,'" said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The bee's compound eye, which can see in any direction and at an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays a vital role in this.
To mimic the function of the compound eye, researchers took up the idea of the laser-guided distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a 180° field of vision of 2 metres, calculates their distances and sends signals to the on-board microprocessor which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is detected in a fraction of a second, and the Autobot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of bees, by turning the tires at the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
"If it wasn't, the Autobot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles", explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Autobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, because this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The whole process has to mirror the behavior of the bees when they're avoiding other bees.
And it has to happen in a split second.
However, unlike the bees, the evasion cannot be up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the tires' flexibility.
While the bees here have an infinite number of ways to evade other bees, the researchers were able to use only rotational motion, or acceleration and deceleration, in the Autobot.
The BR23C contains lithium-polymer batteries which are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer lifetime than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it is more about the instinctive, intelligent response, and less about the processing of the data, and even less about the ability to store it.
This device only has to process and respond to a few inputs per second.
It doesn't need to store it, or produce an intuitive, logical response from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a handful of kilobytes of memory on the fly.
It doesn't need gigabytes and megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in series production within the next ten years.
Another application of the technology could be in GPS satellite navigation, where the driver is deliberately guided around obstacles to reach the destination.
