According to the Central Statistics Office, domestic sales prices in August 2008 increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to August 2007, by 12.9 percent.
Export prices were 1.1% higher than those in July 2008 and 3.9% lower than the previous year's prices.
Due to the changes in prices in the domestic and export sectors, production prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than in 2007.
Domestic sales prices increased only slightly, i.e. by 0.1%, compared with the previous month.
The sales prices of manufacturing industries have also increased only slightly - by 0.1 per cent - since July.
The biggest price increase in August 2008 was for leather goods (2.8 percent) - mainly bags and belts - where the increase was 4.6 percent, while for shoes prices rose by 2.5 percent.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials drove up prices for chemicals and manufacturing considerably (1.6%).
Prices fell in crude oil processing (1.4%), electrical and technical equipment (0.9%) and, to a lesser extent, wood processing (0.1%).
Prices in papermaking, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
In other branches of manufacturing industry, price increases were measured between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the main domestic industrial markets, such as electricity, gas, steam and water supply, prices rose by 0.3% in August, mainly as a result of the gas price increase introduced on 1 July.
Looking at domestic sales markets of manufacturing industry year on year, prices in crude oil processing increased the most (32.4 per cent).
The metal processing sector saw a 13.2 percent increase, while the increase in food, beverage, and tobacco production was 11 percent.
Prices fell in the textile industry (2.5%) and in electrical and technical equipment (0.3%).
