The President of the Republic expresses his 'great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to the protection of injured workers, to the assistance to the families of the victims and to the awareness of public opinion'.
"A certain indignation has arisen, understandably in the case of tragedies which, by their magnitude, generate a certain amount of media and public concern, but in everyday life we are often confronted with dramatic events which, in their own dynamic, can even repeat themselves".
Napolitano does not hide that "there is certainly a resource problem: there is a crucial need to invest in education and information".
The numerous initiatives to raise awareness in schools by young people who are entering the world of work are particularly important.
It is our duty to draw attention to this phenomenon and not to distract from its social gravity.
The President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed that "the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency which offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards definitive rules aimed at putting an end to the problem".
"The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not exclude the fact that the number of workrelated deaths is much too high", stresses Anmil President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this 'positive trend' to mean less attention, which is what causes the tragedy in the end".
"We believe that there is little that can be done to combat the phenomenon of accidents.
We believe that more controls and inspections are necessary, says Mercandelli, but also more measures to educate workers, starting from school".
'Further efforts are needed in terms of communication and raising public awareness.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers is needed in the face of a phenomenon which constitutes a social emergency".
Mr Mercandelli also spoke of the "progressive deterioration of the protection for the victims of industrial accidents" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we have been fighting in recent years".
"The aim is therefore to give the employee a guarantee of insurance, so that the fate of the victim of an industrial accident does not depend on voluntary or accidental donations decided from time to time by a legislator".
MP3 players under indictment: risk of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a long period of time with portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can cause permanent hearing damage.
The European Commission, in a report published today in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the European Union's Scientific Committee on Current and Recently Identified Health Risks.
"The report  states in a footnote  that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music for more than an hour a week for at least five years with portable music devices risk permanent hearing loss".
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who routinely turn portable music devices and cell phones to a high volume are unknowingly damaging their hearing irreparably", says Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific findings, "the EU says, "show a clear risk that calls for urgent action.
What really matters is to educate the consumer and make this information public.
In the light of this scientific knowledge, we must re-examine existing control systems to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with new technology.'
The independent scientific committee was appointed by Brussels in view of the widespread use of portable musical instruments among young people.
'The scientists confirm that their concern is justified and that the European Commission, together with the other Member States and those concerned, will now examine the measures needed to protect children and young people better from the noise emitted by portable musical instruments and similar devices.'
The Commission has already adopted a European standard limiting the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB.
The damage can be greatly reduced by using solutions such as reducing the volume and the duration of the exposure.
In its report, the EU Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable musical equipment listen to music for only five hours a week at a loud volume (above 89 decibels), then the legal limits for maximum noise levels at work have already been exceeded.
Those who go beyond this limit risk losing their hearing completely within five years.
This would amount to 5-10% of the users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
Roma, Alemanno gives the go-ahead to the 'Commission for the Future of the Capital'
We start today, we're supposed to be done by March, we're supposed to be done by June.
This is the procedure established by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of the Capital of Rome". The Commission met this morning at the new headquarters behind the Caracalla Baths.
In six months' time, President Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will be drawing up the guidelines for Rome.
Once the project is completed, the City Council and the Municipal Council will evaluate the analyses and projects in order to be able to present the strategic plan for Rome in June, with the 'official stamp' of the Capitol and the Mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is absolutely independent and all political, social and cultural opinions are represented in it", stresses Alemanno. "It will put forward proposals for a development plan for Rome, for which the political responsibility will remain with the City Council and the Municipality.
There is no redistribution of responsibilities, only the will to have a place to develop a great project for Rome.
In March its task will be completed and the Commission will dissolve again, since such a project must have an endpoint in time.
In June, the Lord Mayor announced, we will present the strategic plan, in which we will use the work done by the Commission".
The Commission's powers are called into question because their opinion is not binding, but Mr Alemanno replies: 'Everything depends on the work the Commission will do and on the quality of its proposals.
If it produces quality results, as the Attali Commission in France did, and this will certainly be the case in Rome, then its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often, politics is concerned with the everyday problems and emergencies that arise from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to look at a longer period of time, so that we can work seriously on the development of Rome and the future of the city in a more profound perspective".
The Mayor of Rome is very careful to clarify that 'this Commission is neither a useless institution nor a wreck: it is absolutely free, it will cost the citizens of Rome not a penny and it will make us think.
According to Alemanno, "it is necessary to have a strategic plan that is neither hermetic nor static in order to enable our city to make a leap in quality - which it really needs - and thus take a joint step into the future".
A future, said the Mayor of Rome, which 'will not be confined to the present municipal boundaries but will look much further,' not only in terms of Rome's role as a metropolis and the political capital of Italy, but also as the future capital of Europe and the Mediterranean.'
