The financial collapse is also affecting journalists: the newspapers are already showing the cuts, and many blame the Internet for the "killer" of the print media.
Five hundred American journalists were interviewed by the PEW Research Center about their situation and their mental control regarding the future.
Today, almost all journalists are pessimistic about their future.
However, they did not express any real concern about the general credibility of the information concerning the authorities.
They don't feel as alone as they used to.
The problem for American journalists is money.
The crisis of 2008 is for these journalists a crisis of an economic model that has been destroyed.
The big problems are compounded by the cuts in the newsroom, the room where the editors work to put the paper together.
This is a problem that needs to be solved, according to the journalists interviewed, if we are to prevent the shrinkage of traditional journalism as it is understood by the general public.
A clear but complicated pessimism is now permeating the American journalist.
Six out of ten journalists and senior executives in the print media believe that journalism at the national level is on the wrong track.
In the local area, it is as high as 65% among executives.
Printed vs. broadcast.
It's not hard for journalists to imagine the direction the Web is going.
The main publishing groups are opening their doors to the Internet, which is considered by many to be the "killer" of the print media.
The "economic pressure" felt by journalists has increased by up to 79%.
The 500 journalists interviewed admitted to wanting to join the new technology in the hope that "it will bring something good for journalism".
The biggest rift in American journalism today is between the editors-in-chief of the newsroom and the reporters who work for them.
56% of editors at national level are confident that their reporters share their values, compared to only 23% at local level.
Some think it has to do with "job security".
The percentage of managers who fear losing their jobs within three years is 47% at national level.
For journalists, it is 30%.
The issue of "safe work" in teams (our "editorial staff", ed.) is always a topical issue in the USA.
Only 13% of journalists are contracted.
In a huge nation like the United States, with 300 million inhabitants and thousands of newspapers, magazines, radio and TV stations and Internet operators, employers offer whatever they like and so it becomes a matter of take it or leave it.
The editors-in-chief often receive very high salaries, whereas the editor may sometimes receive only 10,000 euros a month, plus pension and insurance payments.
The problem of holidays is complicated: a certain number of days in the first year, so many after the third, to reach 15 holidays after a certain number of years.
But American journalists, as they themselves admit, often "fall ill" during the year.
It's a matter of climate.
