The Elite Is in Danger
The phenomenon was already evident a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion White House austerity package: a large section of the American people was and is more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's New York Times, which reported how the crisis is gradually dividing the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored the state institutions and the business community, and those neoconservatives who are hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world and especially in the South and the center of the states, is gaining voters.
This section of the party owes its rise to the voice of the man I mentioned above.
But this example is only a small part of the great changes that the present economic earthquake is heralding or even already represents: not only in the United States, but throughout the West and perhaps beyond.
In the States as well as in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the long-feared events which, under these new conditions, are finally taking shape and coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means the collapse of banking and financial institutions which have close links with the outside world and at the same time manage a huge amount of the wealth of private households resident in a single State.
This poses an immediate political problem for governments: how to deal with the families concerned, who are also a huge constituency.
The crisis thus appears to be global in economic terms, but it is almost purely national in political terms.
Political internationalism seems to have been sidelined and has lost its voice: the clearest proof of this is given by the EU, which, due to its division into various national and international conflicts, is unable to find a common path.
The European Parliament has been a great help to the people of Europe, and it has been a great help to the people of the United States, and it has been a great help to the people of Europe.
And besides the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: two conditions which cannot be overridden under certain circumstances, which no other international organization or market will be able to use in a similar way.
The new emphasis on the national-state element is perfectly in keeping with the growing importance attached recently to a closely related sector of the economy: territoriality.
It is paradoxical that, at a time when we have been so convinced that we have entered a networked realm, a realm of increasingly differentiated technologies, of the intangible, we must suddenly realise that our future will depend more and more on the essentially material things: water, crops and oil.
These can all be transported from one place to another in the world, but they are nevertheless bound to a narrowly defined piece of land.
So the one who has such territory has an advantage over another who lives in a barren, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second innovation, which, however, requires a short introduction.
If you say territory, if you say government, if you say politics, you also say leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respectable leadership, the need for someone who knows how to run things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of resentment against the existing leadership, especially that of the economy, which has proved to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
The European Community is a great example of a Community which is not only a political but also a political one, and which is not only a political but also a political one.
The way seems to be clear for the conviction of large sections of the population that it is not the actions of the social elite but rather their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is increasingly foreign and outdated to the majority.
The demand for leadership is thus feeding a branched but powerful underground movement of disempowerment of the ruling class and the conventional political establishment, manifested in unforeseen "revolts" of the electorate and the sudden upheaval of the collective mood of recent times, from the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, to the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, to the rebellion of the American MPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role).
The impression is given that the old elite, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their magazines, their intellectual credos, some would say their format, have more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value in relation to what is happening today in the lower social layers of the West, and is being intensified by the financial crisis and pushed to overdimensionality.
In view of all this, it would be simply an exaggeration to speak of a "mass rebellion".
But keeping your eyes wide open is not.
The super glue that blows up walls
Defeating the forces of gravity with a little glue and being able to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which seems to be almost there.
With a piece of glue spread over an area of only one square inch, researchers have been able to fix a 300-pound body onto a vertical wall.
The study, published in the American Journal of Neuroscience, reports on the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of the glue can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged in a stack of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the gecko's feet, which are covered with microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, teflon, and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the reptile's foot grip and "can be removed from the wall without any problems", says Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe, but the researchers are thinking about less fascinating uses, like connecting electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could fall within the realm of space.
So for now, the superheroes have to wait.
The University of California, Berkeley, is also studying a new species of tapeworm.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, scientists in California present a microfiber adhesive that, like a hair, cleans itself of dust by moving on a surface, thus maintaining a perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in summer for their refreshing qualities and vitamin content, can cause serious damage to health when taken at the same time as certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, has repeatedly pointed out the risk of both packaged and fresh fruit juices associated with drug use, and at the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again sounded the alarm that a glass of apple, orange, or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption of certain vital drugs to the point of virtually eliminating them, thus endangering the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice has been suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some medicines such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytics and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
MEDICAL REPORTS IN THE COUNTRY  The same drug agency issued a report two years ago warning doctors and patients of the dangers of this mixture, stressing that they should be careful about what they drink in conjunction with such drugs as diazepan or methadone.
It's NOT ONLY FRUIT  Experts say that orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by the fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, Director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually passed on immediately to the various international manufacturers, who are then free to change the consumer information.
It is therefore advisable to read the package leaflet and, if there are any uncertainties, to ask a pharmacist or doctor", stresses the Ansa expert.
The Nobel Prize in Economics is awarded to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics is awarded to American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the settlement of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the most vocal critics of the Bush administration's economic and foreign policies.
A few months after the September 11, 2001 attacks, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman claimed in a New York Times editorial that the second event was more decisive for U.S. history than the attacks.
The answer to this prediction, which was the subject of considerable controversy and which was still presented to economists years later, has now proved to be absolutely correct.
"I am surprised and shocked at how quickly the memory of the Enron or Worldcom scandals has disappeared from public view", said Krugman in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value", but also a trivializing figure with a "very aggressive style, particularly directed against the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration".
Open Office, the third version of the "anti-Microsoft" package is available
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software is gaining an ever-growing number of users as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in public administration.
After a year of intensive work by volunteer developers, supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presented to the public with some new features: in addition to a revised and now more spartan start menu, it is now finally compatible with Apple's Mac OS x operating system, and supports the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, the latest standard ISO version.
The Commission also noted the compatibility with Microsoft Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Some new features are also interesting, such as the one that allows to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes it easier to send via email, for example. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
This is also the case for the creation of hybrid PDF files, which extend the typical graphic formats of Adobe by incorporating the elements of a spreadsheet and a word processing system.
Cooperation is one of the most important improvements in the applications: tables can now be edited by several users, thus avoiding conflicts in the case of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a task to guarantee a better correction process.
Some companies are in the process of publishing various OpenOffice features on the cloud, and the final results are due to be published in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html.
The program is available for the Linux operating system as well as for Windows and Mac OS.
The installation CDs can be sent to your home or office on request.
However, while the free of charge may be an incentive for the distribution of the program in private households, it is also in the field of business where OpenOffice could make a big jump: after all, various public administrations and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training, which is an excellent help for small and medium-sized enterprises and thus even opens up business opportunities.
OpenOffice is made up of five main components: Writer, the word-like word processor; Calc, the spreadsheet program, which aims to supplant Excel; Impress, for creating presentations like Powerpoint; Dbase for running databases in place of the more familiar Access; and lastly Draw, a graphics module.
The target for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads - a target which can be easily exceeded with the 3 million and 600 thousand already reached.
Kohl also tested positive, making him the fourth doping case in the history of the European Union.
A new doping case has been opened in the context of the last Tour de France: it concerns the Austrian athlete Bernhard Kohl of the Gerolsteiner team, who finished third and won the best climber's jersey.
The news was published on the website of the daily newspaper L'Equipe.
The 26-year-old Kohl from Team Gerolsteiner is the fourth rider to test positive for Cera, the third-generation EPO, after Italians Riccardo Riccò and Leonardo Piepoli and Germany's Stefan Schumacher.
The analysis of the blood samples taken from Kohl's body is one of those made in the last few weeks by the laboratories of Losanna and Chattenay-Malabry.
If the counter-tests confirm the positive results on Cera, the Austrian will lose his third place and be banned from the races for two years.
The head of the French anti-doping commission, Pierre Bordry, confirmed the positive result and also informed the Austrian authorities, according to the Associated Press.
The 26-year-old Austrian climbed the podium behind the Spaniard Carlos Sastre and the American Cadel Evans and also claimed the best climber's jersey for himself.
