Italy, "the former country of emigrants, has recently become one of the preferred countries for immigrants", who are only reluctantly accepted.
This is the question posed by the New York Times in a long article devoted entirely to the subject of racism in Italy, based on the case of the young man from Burkina Faso, Abdul William Guibre, who was murdered in Milan a month ago after stealing a package of biscuits.
The case illustrates what the Times calls the "Northern Paradox": the northern regions are those with "the most integration and employment opportunities", yet "the highest levels of anti-immigrant sentiment and the highest level of support for Lega Nord".
