Students are victims of high rents of up to 900 euros per room
The student housing market is not in crisis.
According to the latest research by Sunia, the tenants' union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken very serious forms, with whole groups of students losing their right to study because their families are unable to support them in this amount", says the head of Sunia, Laura Mariani. "In these cities, the high demand from students leads to a distortion of the market that has also harmed other residents.
In addition, most leases involve a number of violations: free contracts, lack of registration, no rent limit, unauthorized subletters.
Sunia considers that exceptional measures are necessary, which will lead to lower rental prices through a revision of the taxation system.
A closer look at the survey reveals that in Milan a place to sleep in the Brianza district costs about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera districts or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the university districts, a bed costs between 250 and 280 euros, and a single room between 370 and 500 euros.
In Rome, the prices in the districts around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double room.
The rents in the neighbourhoods around the other universities of Rome are only slightly lower: €550 in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who move to the outer districts can save money: 300 euros for a bed and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples, you need 300-450 euros for a place to sleep, and for a room, the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive areas, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, a bed costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest towns, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more frequent, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: rent is 25-30% above average for foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso  the cities are closing their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas are closing down due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes".
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of the exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-screen complexes in the periphery, means in the long run the death of the single-screen cinema in the centre, a process which not only seems inevitable and irreversible, but also bears the marks of a cultural crime.
The film is about a suburban cinema and its nostalgia for a cinema that has been lost forever. "It is like losing a friend with whom you have traveled a road full of emotions", says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which won him the Oscar and the Grand Prix at Cannes 20 years ago.
The figures provided by the central trade association, the Anec, speak for themselves: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have had to close down, largely because of the cost of the closures in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The regions most affected are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely in these three regions that the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 are in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way", says Anec's president, Paolo Protti, "and while it is useful that new structures are also created, the first priority is to preserve the existing one, because if a cinema closes in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to go to a multiplex cinema on the periphery instead of the old one.
And here we have the lack of budget for the fund of the trade union: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not observe the existing laws.
To maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed".
The case of Bologna is interesting, as it is the first Italian city to decide, because of the fear of the old cinemas, to protect them by means of an agreement between the municipality and the ANEC, the first agreement of its kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax benefits for cinema operators and transport benefits for the public: driving in the restricted areas of the centre will be allowed and parking will be reduced.
"It is a very exciting initiative", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow our example and develop new concepts.
But of course, we also need better audio and video equipment to counter the superpower of the multiplex theater, because after all, today's audiences are more demanding.
The defence of the traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between the politicians and the 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to align the decisions of the municipality with the interests of the Piromalli mafia group.
The accusations of the public prosecutor's office of the anti-mafia authority of Calabria against the mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in Mafia business, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the senior intermediary between the clan and the public administration, was also arrested, as was his nephew: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the clan boss, had already been convicted of involvement in criminal associations of the mafia, at that time for a compensation sum of 10 million euros.
