When the energy from the waves comes out, the big ones suddenly start to go up.
It's an inexhaustible source of money that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and it's only now that the world's major energy companies seem to grasp this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and even looking to buy, from giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years, and it is no coincidence that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
The idea of marine energy was abandoned when oil prices collapsed in the 1980s, but now environmental organisations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy demand could be met by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be twice the amount of energy currently produced by nuclear power stations.
Add to that the currents and tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to turn to marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary move.
Two years later, more and more companies in the traditional energy sector are turning to marine energy.
"Chevron is looking at these technologies", a spokesman for a company known to the US giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering the possibility of working with us".
The issue is to obtain the approval from the American Energy Commission necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially when you consider that oil is still being produced in Alaska by the United States and that President Bush has just recently started plans for new drilling.
Besides Chevron, the firms Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also investing in the new industry, although although the details are not known, observers are saying that there is a growing interest.
Technologies that still need to be improved.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts of environmentalists have not yet been resolved.
So far, projects like those in Portugal and Scotland have been rather small and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, large-scale energy production requires technologies with a far greater environmental impact.
There are several ways to do this: Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure inside the swimmer via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn drives a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
The Commission has already proposed four such plants, which are awaiting approval from the State, and some of the energy generated could be used for military installations.
Verdant Power, however, is already producing power for a department store and a parking garage by using undersea turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water during the tides drives the turbines, which, through the resulting rotational motion, feed the generator.
According to Verdant, there is already a long line of potential clients waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
The Institute for Power Generation Research says that the potential of tides is of particular interest at the moment.
Although irregular, tides are more predictable than wind currents, sunlight, and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is tidal energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest already $7.5 million in 2008  already up to $35 million is planned for 2009.
